he%20current%20policy%2C%20Meta%20removes%20instances%20of%20%26quot%3Bshaheed%26quot%3B%20when%20referring%20to%20people%20who%20are%20deemed%20dangerous.%20However%2C%20the%20oversight%20board%20argued%20that%20this%20approach%20is%20overly%20broad%20and%20restricts%20freedom%20of%20expression%20and%20civic%20discourse.%20Co-chair%20Helle%20Thorning-Schmidt%20said%20that%20the%20word%20has%20linguistic%20complexity%20and%20diverse%20meanings%20beyond%20just%20%26quot%3Bmartyr%26quot%3B%20in%20English.%C2%A0The%20board%20recognized%20that%20while%20%26quot%3B%3Cem%3Eshaheed%3C%2Fem%3E%26quot%3B%20might%20sometimes%20glorify%20violent%20acts%2C%20it%20is%20also%20used%20in%20neutral%20contexts%20such%20as%20reporting%2C%20academic%20discussions%2C%20and%20human%20rights%20debates.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20board%20stated%20that%20Meta's%20existing%20policies%20against%20inciting%20violence%20and%20support%20for%20designated%20terrorists%20and%20terror%20outfits%20are%20sufficient%20to%20address%20the%20risks%20associated%20with%20terrorist%20activity%20on%20its%20platforms.%20They%20urged%20Meta%20to%20reconsider%20its%20approach%20to%20moderation%20to%20prevent%20the%20removal%20of%20content%20that%20does%20not%20endorse%20terrorism%20or%20violence.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20response%20to%20these%20recommendations%20from%20the%20board%2C%20Meta%20is%20considering%20changes%20to%20its%20policy%20regarding%20the%20use%20of%20the%20word%20on%20its%20platforms.%20The%20board%20suggests%20that%20Meta%20should%20only%20remove%20content%20containing%20the%20term%20if%20the%20posts%20are%20associated%20with%20clear%20signs%20of%20violence%2C%20such%20as%20imagery%20of%20weapons%2C%20statements%20advocating%20violence%2C%20or%20references%20to%20attacks.%20Removal%20should%20also%20occur%20if%20the%20post%20violates%20other%20platform%20rules%2C%20such%20as%20glorifying%20terrorism.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20follows%20years%20of%20criticism%20directed%20at%20Met